article.headline: California 62, Oregon 60
article.story: EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Despite a sub-par offensive performance from its star player, a second-half injury to its best shooter, and a swaying backboard during game-sealing free-throw attempts, Cal survived to hand Oregon a 62-60 loss at McArthur Court on Saturday. Ayinde Ubaka scored 20 points and Leon Powe recorded 15 points and nine rebounds to lead the Golden Bears (14-6, 8-3 Pac-10). It was Cal's fourth straight win and its fifth in seven conference road games. The Golden Bears remain tied with Stanford for second place in the conference, setting up a pivotal matchup between the two teams on Thursday in Berkeley. "I'm going to go home, get in my bed and go to sleep. Then I'll think about Stanford," said a tired Powe, who fell one rebound short of his seventh-straight double-double. Although Powe was only 6 of 18 from the field, he hit a couple of key field goals late in the game to help the Golden Bears hold off the Ducks as they attempted to rally. Powe's jumper with 3:42 to play gave Cal a 53-47 lead and stopped a 7-2 run by Oregon (10-13, 4-7). He then hit an 18-foot jumper with 1:28 to play after the Ducks had cut its deficit to 54-51. Cal sealed the win by making 6-of-7 free-throw attempts in the final 43 seconds, including one by Theo Robertson with four seconds left to give the Bears a 62-59 advantage while the crowd of 9,087 stomped hard enough to visibly shake the backboard. "The rim was shaking while he was shooting," Ubaka said. "That was a tough crowd. They were loud." Ubaka, who has been hobbled this season by a right ankle sprain, aggravated the injury midway through the second half and had to sit out eight minutes. He returned to make a pair of free throws with 17 seconds left. "We just gutted it out," Ubaka said. DeVon Hardin added 10 points for the Golden Bears, while Maarty Leunen led the Ducks with 15 points and nine rebounds. It was the fifth straight loss for Oregon and the second in row that's come by a field goal or less. "It's tough when you lose by single digits," Leunen said. "We have to make better plays towards the end." Oregon, which outshot (47-44 percent) and outrebounded (33-27) Cal, led 24-17 following a layup by Brandon Lincoln 6:08 before halftime. But Ubaka hit a floater on Cal's next possession, igniting a 14-4 run to end the half. Ubaka scored 10 of his 13 first-half points during that stretch, including a 3-pointer at the buzzer to give the Bears a 31-28 lead at the break.
